segments.text: August 29, testing, testing.
Yes, sir.
Testing 1, 2, 3, 4.
This is August 29th, and we're at 905 Carmel.
And I have the honor and pleasure of chatting with General Randolph.
Randolph.
Randolph.
OLPH.
And about his days as a student at Texas A&M.
To begin with,
Describe family and background and growing up and what did mom and dad do?
Brief biographical summary before you came to A&M.
Okay, sir.
It was pretty simple.
I was born in Corpus right at the end of the war, 45, July 45.
My daddy was in essential industry.
He was a petroleum engineer out of LSU.
He was working for Standard Stanley Oil, and he ran oil field camps.
He was the head engineer.
In 46, he moved to Houston.
The family moved to Houston, and he went to work as the chief petroleum engineer for Wesley West.
And so I lived in the same house from 46 to September of 63 when I went to A&M, the same room.
Went to River Oaks Elementary School, Lanier Junior High School, Lamar High School.
Mainly played football, did other sports, but everything was secondary to football.
And then my other interests besides hunting and fishing, which my grandfather, who was a Teddy Roosevelt environmentalist but didn't realize it,
at the time taught me the art and the finer points of the outdoors and hunting and fishing.
enjoying the outdoors, but we, my father bought, started buying some acreage in Grimes County, Texas, 65 miles north of Houston in the 50s.
And by 1957 through 4-H and everything, I was

raising registered Angus cattle and quarter horses and breaking horses and rodeoing and calf roping and really focused on the ranch, the farm and the ranch activities, although living in Houston was spending most of my time, especially after I got my driver's license, up at the ranch.
Came to Texas A&M
The first time I ever came here, I was swimming.
I was a high school swimmer because that was one thing that didn't conflict with football as far as the seasons went.
And I came to the state meet.
The Texas state meet was in the old dungeon where the zone sits on top of my swimming pool now.
The P.L.
Downs Natatorium.
Right.
And that was my first trip, and I saw the cadets and everything, but was focused on the swimming meet.
What was your impression from that visit?
That very orderly place.
I'd been to Rice.
I'd played football at the Rice University, Rice Institute Stadium.
And so that was in my hometown, and I'd seen a lot of Rice.
And so when I came to A&M, I thought it was a very disciplined campus compared to the Rice campus.
That was my two comparisons.
But you had no A&M family.
No.
My mother and dad went to LSU.

my brother my older brother went to Tulane and so I it was my senior year at a high school that I said well I want to be a veterinarian because I was kind of that's all I really enjoyed doing was working on horses and I was going to be my goal was to be a
A rodeo veterinarian.
I knew I wasn't a good enough calf roper to make it big time calf roping, but I loved to do it.
And I liked rodeo clowning.
I was a clown for four years.
But you couldn't make a lot of money enough to support yourself, so I said, well, I'll be the rodeo vet.
and I'll take care of all the quarter horses on the circuit.
And so I went to, I came up here and I met, who later became my advisor, Dr. Romaine, out at the vet school.
And talked to him and, you know, he figured out right quick I knew a lot about horses and that I was, you know, just had a natural, we went out to the stables and
And he could just tell I knew a lot about horses.
And so he was encouraged me to apply to A&M.
I don't remember anything at all about the application being accepted or anything.
I just know that it was the only place I applied.
If you were a Texan and you wanted to go to vet school, you went to A&M for pre-vet.
I mean, there was no...
You could have gone to Sam Houston State or something and transferred over, but it was kind of a cut-and-dried situation.
And so I came up here.
My mother brought me up.
Just to enroll?
To enroll.
No, just to enroll.
I don't remember.
I probably drove myself up to see Dr. Romain because it takes 35 minutes to get from the farm.
So, you know, on Highway 30, I would just cut through.
And I was in and around this place all the time.
And so I probably came up to see him by myself.
But I remember my mother and Mrs. Jessie Gallagher, who was a nurse, a nurse,
A Houston nurse, longtime friend of the family's, drove me up.
And except for football cleats, I'd never worn shoes.
I'd always worn cowboy boots.
And so my memory of coming on the campus was they cut my hair off.
And I'd never had long hair, but they cut it off.
And I didn't like that.

and um and then they made me wear shoes that we went to you know uh what is the military is called the cif the central issue facility i'm sure i'm not sure what it was called at a m at the time but they issued us our khakis and and you know our uniforms and they they um issued us some black leather shoes and then that day we shined them and and um and i had to wear them and i
I absolutely detested wearing shoes.
I thought they were the worst looking things, and they weren't comfortable.
And being a short guy, I liked the high heels that the cowboy boots gave me, another inch and a half of height.
I didn't get that from the loafer shoes, the military shoes.
But I went into A3 Vet.
Just saying, let me interrupt that.
Now, when you came up that day to enroll,
Who brought you and what stuff did you bring with you?
Well, that's really interesting because today I'd go to jail.
My mother brought me up.
And, you know, the fall is when hunting season starts.
Matter of fact, I'm leaving Friday to break in the 2001 season at our lease in South Texas.
So I came up with my shotgun, my rifle, and I used a straight razor.
That's what I shaved with.
And that's just what I had.
And nobody said anything.
The rifle was a Winchester Model 94.
I'm sure I had five bullets in the magazine.
The shotgun was a Remington Model 31 pump.
It was my granddad's, and I'm sure I had two 7 12s in the magazine.
And they stayed in my closet.
And the only thing, and then that straight razor was in my room there in my foot locker.
And the only thing I remember about that, I mean, the only, there was never a question was having a gun on campus, but the both guns and the straight razor had to be ready for inspection.
So they were the cleanest they'd ever been in their lives because they had to be ready for all those inspections.
And so I always had a couple of things to clean up that other people didn't have.
but nobody said anything, and I don't remember bringing anything else.
You didn't bring no hats, and what about other, did you bring it all in the foot locker, whatever you did bring?
Well, I did, but because our ranch was here, I had all my clothes 35 miles away,
And then, initially, I didn't have a car because it just didn't seem like it wasn't discussed.
But very quickly, I made good enough grades at the break point in the fall semester.
There was a break point there.
And if you made a certain GPR, all of a sudden, you got all kinds of freedoms.
But until that point, we were sequestered.
We never left the campus and everything except I was running these cattle.
these registered cattle.
I mean, they were my cattle.
And so I fairly early on snuck my Jeep, I had a Jeep, and snuck the Jeep onto campus.
And I'm not even sure where I parked it.
I didn't park it behind 17 then.
It was later that I parked it behind 17.
But I would sneak out of Durham 17 at 1 o'clock in the morning.
go check my cattle, just make the rounds with the headlights, and be back by three or four, you know, and we just, nobody know the difference.
And I didn't cause any trouble, but, you know, the cattle had to be checked.
I had a fellow, a friend, a neighbor, who I talked to just today, he was feeding them for me.
But, you know, and salting and everything, but, you know, it was my cattle.
So I remember that was kind of an early issue, and then
someone said, well, if you make a certain grade point ratio, you can have a car and you can leave campus.
And I said, during the day?
I mean, you know, like, I could leave, you know, legally?
And so that was my incentive to study real hard.
Now, when your mom left you that day,
Do you remember any advice or counsel that she gave you or your dad had given you the night before?
No, it's interesting.
My brother and I have talked about it.
My dad was a product of the Depression.
You know, he'd gone through World War II, and he did not give advice.
He was a heck of a role model as a work ethic, a work ethic role model.
He was prepared for the next Depression.
He was prepared for the next World War II.
But he wasn't a philosopher.
You know, he didn't give advice.
My mom, mother has, and she's 82 in Houston and is in great health and doing wonderful.
She's had something that she told me then and she's told me a million times since.
And she says everything always works out for the best.
So she says don't worry about things.
I was a certain, to a certain degree, a worrier.
And she knew that, I guess.
And she says, you know, Randy, things will work out for the best.
And then I noticed as things would go on and I would call home, very seldom did I talk to my dad.
But mother, I'd always talk to mom.
And if I ever was feeling down or had a, you know, was going to do something that she didn't think was right, instead of telling me not to do it,
She'd say, sleep on it and call me tomorrow.
Well, by tomorrow, it was okay.
So I think that was the only thing I remember was, you know, everything works out for the best, and if you're down, just sleep on it.
It'll look better tomorrow.
And you got assigned to what outfit?
A3 vet.
John Kieschnick was my company commander.
Did it have a nickname?
Well, you asked that in the paperwork, and I've looked, and if it did, I don't recall.
The only thing I recall about it was like September the 15th or 16th.
We started school in September back then, which I think is wonderful.
The thought of school, I never liked school.
Matter of fact, when I went to kindergarten at River Oaks Elementary, my mother took me.
We walked to school.
And I beat her home the first day of school.
And I announced when she came back, I was sitting on the back steps, that I didn't like school.
And the thought of starting in August would have just killed me.
But we started back then in mid-September.
And John Kieschnick, they'd cut our hair off, and we were in our PT gear, our physical training gear.
And we were on our seats.
And there was, in my...
In A3 Vets, there was about 60 of us, as I recall.
It could have been 40, but I've always thought there was about 60 fish in A3.
And our knees are under our chins, and we've got our arms around our knees.
John Kieschnick's got his boots on, and he's marching back and forth down the hall.
And he said, okay, fish, look to your left, look to your right.
Those guys are going to be missing soon.
And I think out of the...
50 or 60 of us, nine graduated from A&M.

And it always struck me that A&M, and when I would get lieutenants from A&M in the military, I'd always have to caution them that the mission is not to run off people in the Army, the mission is to keep people.
And so, you know, it always struck me that at least that A3 company prided itself
with my fish roommate, about, it was Fish Lillard.
I don't know what his first name was.
He was from Beaumont.
And he lasted about three weeks.
And one weekend, he never came back.
And his folks came back and got his stuff.
But I never saw Fish Lillard again.
But they were so hard on him because he was kind of meek and mild.
And that was not what they wanted in A3.
Mm-hmm.
And so it was, you know, that was kind of the entrance.
And I was a little negative at the end of that meeting, the way it went.
But that night, we went to G. Raleigh White.
We marched to G. Raleigh White.
It was my first night on campus, I think.
And we were all marched in there, and we were sat down.
And the upperclassmen, and I'm not sure if they were the
sophomores and juniors, but the upperclassmen were standing in the aisles and we were sitting in the bleachers looking down at the basketball court.
And General Earl Rudder came out and he got a microphone and he had this, as I remember, this billowing voice and he welcomed us and he told us some of the history of A&M and
And he talked a little bit about what A&M had done, as far as A&M cadets had done in World War II.
And then he says, and I need to tell you a story because some of you are going to want to quit.
And you need to know that Aggies aren't quitters.
And he said, I was given the mission as a young lieutenant colonel to take Pointe du Hoc.
He says, I know none of you have ever been there, and I doubt if any of you know where it is, but it's in France, and it's just off the Normandy beaches to the right of Normandy beaches.
He said there was some German, and I'll never forget this.
I mean, I was mesmerized.
I'm looking down at this guy, and he says there was some German field guns that could range the Allied shipping, and it was in fortified positions.

concrete reinforced bunkers and they allied planes for months in preparing the battlefield had bombed Pointe du Hoc but the Germans to make sure that we knew that it was bombing was a failure every once while we just run one of those big uh coastal artillery pieces out of the end of the bunker and shoot out into the Atlantic
to tell us that they were still fine.
So my rangers, the second ranger battalion that I commanded was given the mission to take it.
And he said, when I looked at the maps, the grid lines stacked on top of one another at the point where the ocean and the land met.
And I know you don't know anything about military maps, but that meant it was a cliff.
And so we began to train in England on cliff climbing.

and he said the Rangers were a tough bunch and had gone through all kind of special training, but then we began, you know, how to get up this cliff, and we knew that they would be, for sure, rolling rocks down on us and probably shooting with the small arms right down on us, so we were going to have to do this at night.
So the training in England progressed from day...
cliff climbing, and we found a suitable place to night cliff climbing.
I had people rolling rocks down on the soldiers.
I mean, he went through all this, and I was mesmerized.
Well, as he's telling the story, a Texas thunderstorm begins to materialize, and it starts lightning, and you can hear the thunder, and then it would lightning, and then it would be pitch dark.
And one of the bolts obviously hit a critical point on campus.
And all the lights in G. Raleigh went out.
All the electricity went out.
And it was pitch dark, except when it was lightning.
And there would be light, and there would be pitch dark, and the thunder, and the tremendous bolts.
And General Rutter never stopped talking.
The microphone went out.
But there was an acoustic, pretty good acoustics there, and his billowing voice just came from that basketball floor.
He was marching back and forth and telling us about climbing up and getting shot at and everything and what his rangers were doing.
And then the lightning would hit, and you'd see him down there, and then it would be pitch dark.
And about the time, you know, the crescendo of his speech and the crescendo of the lightning and the thunder is there and he's ending his speech, all the electricity comes back on and gee raleigh.
He ends his presentation and I remember whoever was next to me, I said to him, this guy's really good.
And I remember thinking, I wonder if he does this every September like this.
But any time from then on, I felt like quitting A&M, the thought would quickly pass because I was afraid I might have to go see General Rutter or something.
And so I never really had serious thoughts of quitting A&M at all.
And I'll never forget that, and I've told that story many a time.
All right, describe how your outfit was put together in the dorm.
You're in what dorm?
17, which is over by the Agriculture Extension Service Building.
But I think it has a name now, but it used to be a number, 17.
And we were at the end of the quad from Sabisa, and then we had the longest way to march to Sabisa.
And did you all have the whole dorm?
Well, you know, I don't know that.
I was on the first floor, and I know we had the whole first floor, and that was enough for me.
Describe your room, what was in it, and so forth.

Well, it was austere because anything you had in it had to be ready for inspection, so nobody in their right mind had extra stuff in this room because if you did, you had to have it cleaned and everything.
And the only thing that I guess I ever really got in trouble for was I loved peanut butter sandwiches.
And I loved them at midnight and 2 or 3 o'clock in the morning or whatever.
And underneath the sink where the plumbing was, there was a metal plate with four screws.
And that's where I kept my bread and my peanut butter.
And then one day, one of the inspections, they noticed the paint, you know, from the screw was chipped.
And so they took the plate off, and there was my peanut butter and my bread.
But the room was, you know, it had two closets.
It had bunk beds and one window and a radiator and had, you know, just blinds, Venetian-type blinds.
And fish weren't allowed any posters or anything.
And you each had a desk right by the radiator there that just faced out.
And I think there was one dresser that you shared.
After your first fish old lady dropped out of school, did they move somebody else in?
Billy Provine from Alexandria, Louisiana.
And he and I are past friends today.
And Billy, I was raised as a hunter and a fisherman and a natural woodsman.
And Billy Provine was five times the hunter and fisherman.
He was from Alexandria.
And we kind of supported ourselves by frogging

in through the years we would and we would sell the bullfrogs in the season to the local restaurants and we we would frog all over you know the farms on the other side of the railroad tracks we knew every little slew and every little pond and we had our frog gigs and
And he had his... Y'all started that as freshmen?
Yeah, we just started... We were both outdoorsmen, and that's what we liked.
So you gigged them and dressed them?
Right.
And there were several little restaurants in Bryan.
Do you remember what the price was you were able to sell them for?
We sold them in a bag, and it was kind of, I think, about a pound.
And so you used...
I don't recall the money, but it was...
It was certainly spending money for us.
I mean, it was just a few dollars, I'm sure.
What was the routine at night in your dorm?

Well, to the credit of the Corps, the Corps was, at least A3 being a vet company, a pre-vet company, and the juniors and seniors were in vet school, that they were pretty disciplined about us studying and
And so there was a call to quarters between a certain time and a certain time.
And I'll say it's like 1930 to 2130 or something that you had to be at your desk with your elbows on your desk studying.
I mean, that was reading and studying and writing.
And that was for like three hours.
And the good news about that was you couldn't be harassed.
No upperclassmen could come in there and harass you.
The only place you could go outside your room was a latrine.
And so it was a focused study time.
Now, let's see.
Now, G7, a year or two later, John Sharp and Rick Perry were in a pre-vet company.
Did you overlap with them?
Not that I know of, no.
Because they were in the same outfit.
Yeah.
I went, you know, 3rd Brigade, at the end of my fish year,
1963, at the end of 64, spring of 64, the Corps went voluntary.
And so the next year when we came back, the Corps was much smaller.
And they had done away with the 3rd Brigade.
And so we moved, I was a sophomore in B-1 vets.
And that was in the New Dorm area.
And Duncan was our mess hall.
And I know the dorm, but I don't recall the number.
but I know where it was.
And so then I was a B1 vet.
But back that fish year, after 1030, there could be some harassment.
What kind of things went on in your life?
Well, we only had one, and I learned a lot about leadership.
Because we had...
I figured out right quick this was a game.
And...
And so I kind of approached it as a game and never really took any of this very seriously, any of this harassment.
There were pissheads who had to harass who didn't like to do it.
And you figured those out.
They were play acting.
They were hollering and whatever, and they were not serious.
And it was just, it was their mission.
They had to do that.
And at the same time, we're doing some coaching and teaching along the way, and you kind of gained...
some admiration and respect for those guys.
Gosney, there was several of them that I admired.
But there was one, his name was Bill Bamberg from Buffalo, New York, and he busted out as a sophomore.
But he was from north of Dallas, and he acted like a Yankee, and he thought like a Yankee, and he thought all that upperclassman stuff was real serious.
And he took it serious, and...
He just, you know, I used to feel sorry for him because he really thought that he was, you know, scaring us and it was all I could do not to laugh in his face, you know.
And I wasn't surprised when he didn't come back because he just didn't fit with the other guys.
So when I got, so I figured out when I was going to be an upperclassman, I was going to be one of those guys that focused on
Coaching and teaching and not harassing, not hollering.
As a military officer, I never hollered at troops because they're not going to listen to that.
Because I learned right quick as a fish.
And I learned it with Texas football.
I had some coaches that hollered and some coaches that taught.
And the ones that taught and coached and mentored, you listened and you learned from.
And the hollers, you kind of wrote them off.
And it was the same thing in my...
So there was some hollering going on, but it never...
I don't ever... And I've looked at my journals.
I never remember...
I never wrote down being mad or being upset or... And I just...
I remember...

having to not laugh though because that didn't make that didn't help you you did a lot of push-ups if you laughed and and thank goodness i was had a strong enough body because i did do a lot of push-ups and that was about the most serious thing that happened and and but i'd done a lot of push-ups in football so i that was not anything that you know now did they use the paddle in your outfit
No, I don't remember the paddle.
Maybe they did, but I don't remember that.

What I remember, the thing that I remember that I didn't like was when you leaned against the wall and they ran the clothes hanger down and they hit that clothes hanger between your fanny and the wall.
Now that hurt.
And the more you pressed against the wall, the more they made you put your feet out and the more weight you put against the wall,
the harder they had to get that clothes hanger down.
And so I don't remember a paddle at all.
Was that a punishment device?
Oh, it was kind of a rites of passage.
I don't remember as punishment as much as you kind of just...
You know, we knew that was going to happen every night.
And it left a pink fanny?
Yeah, oh, I'm sure it did.

I mean, I never looked, but I remembered saying, because I, you know, they had paddles in high school and junior high school, and, you know, I'd been, I had my rounds there, and I remember that the paddle didn't hurt at all compared to this clothes hanger going.
I said, whoever came up with that, you know, was, you know, really was out to impress you.
All right, now, academically, do you remember going through registration your first semester, or were your courses decided by?
No, matter of fact, registration was in Duncan.
